org.jcvi.jillion.core

Class Range

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.jcvi.jillion.core.Range
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, Iterable<Long>, Rangeable

    public abstract class Range
extends Object
implements Rangeable, Iterable<Long>, Serializable
    A Range is a pair of coordinate values which describe a contiguous subset of a sequence of values. Ranges are immutable. Changes to a Range are done using Range.Builder to create new instances.

    Ranges have a begin value and an end value. The start value will always be less than or equal to the end value. The minimum start value of a Range is Long.MIN_VALUE and the max end value of a Range is Long.MAX_VALUE. Also due to limitations to Java primitives, Ranges can not have a length < Long.MAX_VALUE. Any attempt to build Ranges beyond those values will throw Exceptions.

    The Range coordinates are 0-based inclusive. Thus, a Range of 20 to 30 has a size of 11, not 10, and a Range of 42 to 42 will have a size of 1 not 0. This is done to conform with the overwhelming majority use of inclusive ranges in Bioinformatics. The implications of this are particularly important when thinking about the desire to represent no range at all. A Range of 0 to 0 still has a size of 1. In order to represent a Range with length 0, you need to create a Range of length 0 by either using the static factory method Range.ofLength(0) or create a new Range.Builder instance with either the empty constructor or use the methods on the builder to shrink the range to an empty length.

    Often, Bioinformatics formats use non-0-based coordinates. Other coordinate system start and end values can be queried via the getBegin(CoordinateSystem) and getEnd(CoordinateSystem) methods. A different Range.CoordinateSystem can be also be specified at construction time via the of(CoordinateSystem, long, long) method. If this method is used, the input values will automatically get converted into 0-based coordinates.

    Ranges can be constructed using either Range.Builder of through several convenience static factory methods including of(long), of(long, long) , of(CoordinateSystem, long, long) and ofLength(long). All of these methods use Range.Builder internally.

    The actual implementation of Range returned by these methods or the Range.Builder might vary based on input values in order to decrease memory usage. (For example a Range that is very short could represent the length as a byte instead of a long. Or if the range is in positive coordinates then memory could be saved by using unsigned values instead of signed. etc). In addition, since Ranges are immutable, it is not guaranteed that the Range object returned by these creation methods is a new instance since Ranges are often cached (Flyweight pattern). Therefore; Range objects should not be used for synchronization locks. Range objects are cached and shared, synchronizing on the same object as other, unrelated code can cause deadlock. 

     
 //don't do this
 Range range = ...
 ...
   synchronized(range){ 
       ...   
    }
 ...
    Range is Serializable in a (hopefully) forwards compatible way. However, there is no guarantee that the Range implementation will be the same or even that the implementation class will be the same, the the deserialized object should always be equal to the Range that was serialized.
    Author:
    dkatzel, jsitz@jcvi.org

    • Method Detail

      • of

        public static Range of(long start,
                       long end)
        Factory method to get a Range object in the Range.CoordinateSystem.ZERO_BASED coordinate system. If end == start -1 then this method will return an empty range. This method is not guaranteed to return new instances and may return a cached instance instead (flyweight pattern).
        Parameters:
        start - start coordinate inclusive.
        end - end coordinate inclusive.
        Returns:
        a Range; never null but might not be a new instance.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if end < start -1 or if the resulting range length > Long.MAX_VALUE.

      • of

        public static Range of(Range.CoordinateSystem coordinateSystem,
                       long localStart,
                       long localEnd)
        Factory method to build a Range object with the given coordinates specified in the given coordinate system. If after converting the coordinates into 0-based coordinate, end = start -1, then the returned range is equivalent to an empty range at the start coordinate.
        Parameters:
        coordinateSystem - the Range.CoordinateSystem to use.
        localStart - the start coordinate in the given coordinateSystem.
        localEnd - the end coordinate in the given coordinateSystem.
        Returns:
        a non-empty Range instance. This is not guaranteed to be a new instance since Ranges use the flyweight pattern to reuse the same objects.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if coordinateSystem is null.
        IllegalArgumentException - if length is negative
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if the combination of start and length values would cause the Range to extend beyond Long.MAX_VALUE.

        Parameters:

        Throws:

        public static Range parseRange(String rangeAsString,
                               Range.CoordinateSystem coordinateSystem)
        Parses a string in the format <left>[.. | - ]<right>. Any whitespace between the left and right parameters is ignored.
        Examples:
        • 24 .. 35
        • 24-35
        • 24,35
        Parameters:
        rangeAsString - the range to parse.
        coordinateSystem - the Range.CoordinateSystem the coordinates in the String to parse are in.
        Returns:
        a Range; will never be null.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if the given String does not match the correct format.

      • complement

        public List<Range> complement(Collection<Range> others)

      • forEachValue

        public void forEachValue(Range.CoordinateSystem cs,
                         LongConsumer consumer)
        Loop over each offset value in this range using the given coordinate system. This method is preferred over Iterable.forEach(java.util.function.Consumer) because that method must autobox the primitive longs into Long objects; in addition, the coordinate system couldn't be specified.
        API Note:
        this will automatically convert the coordinates of each offset into the given coordinate system. For example if the range is from offsets 0 - 9, then calling this method with a will call the consumer for 1..10.
        Parameters:
        cs - the CoordinateSystem to use; can not be null.
        consumer - the LongConsumer to call for each offset; can not be null.
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if either parameter is null.
